    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-09-04T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-09-04T08:00:00-05:00" n="889"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d889">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.80/9–454: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 889<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France (<persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                            type="from">Dillon</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-09-04T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 4, 1954—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>981. Embassy would urge that proposed statement of U.S. policy re <gloss
                        target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> area (Dept’s <gloss target="#t_cirtel1"
                        >Cirtel</gloss> 125 Sept 1) be discussed with French at same time as with
                    U.K. and Turkey. While unilateral action by U.S. in announcing this policy
                    without previous discussion with French would be unpalatable to them, failure to
                    give them equal opportunity with U.K. and Turkey to comment on statement or make
                    parallel statement or associate themselves with U.S. statement would be omission
                    for which plausible explanation could not easily be found, particularly in view
                    French adherence to Tripartite Declaration referred to in statement.</p>
                <p>Rather than separate statements designed for Israel and Arab States respectively
                    where variance or wording would be carefully weighed for significance, Embassy
                    believes single statement designed for both Israel and Arab consumption would be
                    preferable. This would appear require only limited modifications of present
                    draft, i.e. addition of sentence in point 3 to reflect extension of military aid
                    to Arab States and addition of clause in second para of point 4 to express hope
                    that statement will likewise reassure Arabs on U.S. policy in event Israeli
                    aggression.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dillon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
